<br><div><div>On Jan 17, 2014, at 9:58 PM, Paul Hargrove &lt;<a href="mailto:phhargrove@lbl.gov" target="_blank">phhargrove@lbl.gov</a>&gt; wrote:</div><br><blockquote type="cite"><div dir="ltr">The README in trunk and v1.7 both read:<div>
<br></div><div><div><font face="courier new, monospace">- ROMIO is not supported on OpenBSD.  You will need to specify the</font></div><div><font face="courier new, monospace">  --disable-io-romio flag to configure when building on OpenBSD.</font></div>

</div><div><br></div><div>However, I have no current problems building it:</div><div><br></div><div><div><font face="courier new, monospace">$ ./INST/bin/ompi_info --parsable | grep -e :arch: -e romio</font></div><div><font face="courier new, monospace">config:arch:x86_64-unknown-openbsd5.3</font></div>

<div><font face="courier new, monospace">mca:io:romio:version:mca:2.0</font></div><div><font face="courier new, monospace">mca:io:romio:version:api:2.0</font></div><div><font face="courier new, monospace">mca:io:romio:version:component:1.7.4</font></div>

<div><br></div><div>This item in the README entered v1.5 in r25845 and was syned to trunk in r26034.</div><div>The 02/23/2012 date for r25845 comes weeks AFTER I had resolved problems I was having when testing v1.5 on OpenBSD (<a href="http://www.open-mpi.org/community/lists/devel/2012/01/10300.php" target="_blank">http://www.open-mpi.org/community/lists/devel/2012/01/10300.php</a>).  So, I am not sure why it was decided that ROMIO was broken on OpenBSD in 1.5.</div>

